I think what one wants to say about the frivolity of travel is to fly on holiday, much like getting on a bus and without any sensory awareness of the surroundings, the people and experiences of slower travel, the journey has become unimportant and only the destination matters. If one could beam from one position to another, people would probably do it and also overcome this shock, only to find what they wanted to leave at home. The common holidaymaker is not looking for the foreign, the surprising, the frightening or the unfamiliar. That may be the answer to why something is perceived as frivolous: Pure consumption, travel as an economic end in itself.

That said, I still wouldn't want to forbid anyone or find arguments to condemn someone for it. Everyone has to know what they are doing and why they are doing it. I stopped flying, a conscious decision, but I wouldn't give up travelling because of it. Just find another way. The many moralisers who now want this or that regulated and forbidden, maybe they are just working off their guilty conscience of having indulged in things they don't really stand by.

Anyone who runs a restaurant, hotel or other business as a small or medium-sized entrepreneur probably didn't do it to become a millionaire, but to feed himself or his family and to have a purpose in life. Culture is contained in this and it will die if we continue to lock ourselves in.

The metropolises and megacities are not a good place to be at the moment, they probably weren't for a long time before, where everything is designed for conformity and sameness. We humans need the diversity and the unexpected, the many different talents and efforts on this beautiful planet. I discovered your vlog just a few days ago and thank you so much for your films. They give me something of the world that I didn't know yet and it's the amateurishness of it that is the good.

I live in America and I have seen and experienced the damage it has caused on people’s livelihoods. Businesses have closed, jobs have been lost. "POST-SOVIET Monstrosity" : The BIGZ Building - it actually is a building located in Belgrade. Designed by Dragiša Brašovan, it is one of the most representative architectural landmarks of Serbian modern architecture. A monumental building, with its position, volume and aesthetics, it dominates the entrance in the southern section of Belgrade.

It has been protected since 1992. In recent times it represents a significant cultural, artistic and social spot.

Construction began in June 1936. The building was finished in May 1940, but the equipment wasn't installed until February 1941. It was the first building in Serbian architecture which consistently implemented structural frame made of reinforced concrete. As the building is massive and robust, to accommodate large number of printing presses which were very large themselves at the time, it is also quite heavy. The solution for the structural load was over one meter thick plate of reinforced concrete on which the entire building rests. To ease the pressure, Brašovan designed the building in the shape of the Cyrillic letter P (П), which also was the shape of the printing press.

Up until this year, I had been like you - constantly in motion around the world for the past four years. For me, I’ve decided to put travel on hold for the foreseeable future because of Covid. Granted, I had started to reach a point in my life where I started to want a little more stability, so the timing of the pandemic just seemed to add fuel to that fire. But there still have been many moments this year when I’ve missed that feeling of being out on the road and interacting with people from far off places.

Like many travelers, I do feel conflicted about this. On one hand, I know travel can have such a transformative effect on someone’s life so I never want to discourage anyone from doing it if they have the chance. But on the other hand, travel right now is one of the driving factors in why this pandemic is even happening.

I lean toward caution because I’ve had the opportunity to see a lot of the world already - much more than the average person. This point and time for me is a period of rest I guess. And I get that there are people out there who don’t feel that same way and want to travel. Again, I’m not writing to shame or discourage those people from doing so.

Ultimately, everyone will do what they feel is best for them. There are no exact right or wrong answers in this situation - only well-educated guesses. And accepting that two things that are total opposites can be equally true can help with managing the tension that we all feel between deciding to travel or stay put during this pandemic.

Eva, I love watching your videos. You do great work.
But I think I have a bit of a disagreement with your plaintiff pleas regarding the travel industry. I am trying to travel 2 months per year. It is the great thing about retirement.
I think that responsible travelers decide not to travel right now. The Covid epidemic makes it unsafe. The medical risks and financial complications of getting covid in a foreign country can be life threatening. When travelling it is not possible to stay away from people and protect oneself as effectively as at home. When traveling it is necessary to take precautions not to catch covid in unfamiliar situations and simultaneously explore the sights and cultures that one is visiting. I believe this creates experiences which are inferior to those of normal travel.
I believe that a broader perspective about industries lead to the following. The only thing that is constant is change! It is normal that industries need to adjust as world events cause variation in the demand for the industry. I myself have experienced industry changes 3 times which caused an end to my employment and a need to find a new way to contribute to society. In my case these changes were permanent. By contrast covid is causing intense pain in a multitude of industries but it is temporary. The latest news suggests that vaccines will be broadly available in April. This predicts a return to normal for many of those industries. I plan to spend a month in Europe in the middle of next year once I have received the vaccine. This is not magic, it is the scientifically driven medical industry.
You and your friends are not alone. I have relatives who are professional actors and have received zero income since March. Many of my neighbors have been unemployed from various non-entertainment businesses since March. Retired people who have limited years of travel remaining, want to travel but cannot. They adopt the philosophy that they are protecting their safety by not travelling. Owners of retail and service businesses continue to have business expenses,. but have zero or low business income..
Having said all this might I suggest that creative travel bloggers/vloggers might motivate travelers with ideas to be used in 8-12 months. Those ideas might include: 1. How to travel safely, 2. Destinations for after the pandemic, 3. What to do when you feel ill during travel, 4. The difference between safe and less safe destinations/activities.
Thanks for your suggestions and for sharing your perspective! I absolutely respect your choice and hope that you can travel again in the future on your own terms!

Your hotel was once part of the "post-Soviet monstrosity". When Belgrade was smaller, that used to be one of the industrial areas, and the whole building used to be a printing mill. It was built before World War II, and its architect is probably the greatest name of Yugoslav architecture. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BIGZ_building Welcome to Serbia, hope you have a great time here!

Thanks for this correction. Its a shame „soviet“ or actually socialist architecture gets such a bad reputation everywhere. Architects from those eras put a lot of thought and consideration into their projects and many of those „monstrosities“ are actually very useful and comfortable homes, working places or places of leisure, albeight often in desperate need of renovation. Looking at the terrible shiny plastic stuff that has been built since 1990 like Beograd na vodi one would wish some ideas of socialist architecture would actually be revisited.

There are good examples for how to do it: Japan or South Korea have had no lockdown but much lower numbers than us. They also all wear masks. Masks will not protect you 100% but they are proven to significantly lower the probabiliy of acquiring covid (or any respiratory infection, thats why doctors wear them...) and it is also probable that mask can also lead to less severe outcomes of covid because the initial virus dose is lowered. Btw Sweden is far from laissez-faire these days with covid. They dont have lockdowns but have a lot of specific measures to stop the spread of the virus.

The main problem about covid is that - if you just let it spread like a regular flu - it will lead to a total overload of hospitals and emergency services. It has proven to do so in spring in italy, NYC or alsace and it is now on the way to do so in Switzerland and other countries. Once hospitals are full not only a lot more covid deaths will happen but also non-covid-deaths, young people with accidents and other emergencies will start dying in much higher numbers bc hospitals are full.
Btw there are clear statistics in terms of covid deaths from the first outbreak in march. Just look up excess mortality in places like Bergamo or NYC. In some places there were 5-10 times more people dying than in regular months of all causes. The reason why this didnt happen everywhere is obviously that governments and people reacted.
